      <h2>Miter Saw Tiers at a Glance</h2>
      <p><strong>Entry-Level (under $200):</strong> The Metabo HPT 10-inch single bevel handles trim and light framing for service contractors who need a lightweight, portable saw. The SKIL MS6305-00 adds sliding and dual-bevel capability at a similar price point, making it the best value for homeowners tackling crown molding and baseboard projects.</p>
      <p><strong>Mid-Range ($200-$400):</strong> The DEWALT DWS715 delivers professional-grade power and durability in a non-sliding 12-inch format. The DEWALT DWS779 adds sliding and dual bevel for the same price as many competitors 10-inch saws, making it the most popular model among full-time framers and trim carpenters.</p>
      <p><strong>Premium ($400+):</strong> The DEWALT DWS780 and cordless options serve specialized needs. The DWS780 is the shop standard for heavy daily use. Cordless models trade some cutting capacity for mobility, making them the right choice for remodeling contractors who work across multiple job sites.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>The right miter saw depends on whether you are trimming out a single room or framing an entire house. For most contractors and serious DIYers, the DEWALT DWS779 provides the best balance of capacity, power, and price with its 12-inch sliding dual-bevel design. If portability is the priority, the Metabo HPT 10-inch model cuts 20 pounds off the weight without sacrificing cut quality for trim work. And for homeowners with a budget cap, the SKIL MS6305-00 delivers sliding dual-bevel capability at half the price of premium brands. Match the saw to the workload, and you will make back the investment in saved time on the first few projects.</p>

